      "content": "it's hard to believe it's just coincidence when the pattern is this consistent. i was reading about how some smart devices have microphones for voice assistants, and even if they aren't \"recording,\" they're still processing audio patterns to detect wake words. could acoustics from something like crying or even just heavy breathing be used as a trigger for other devices on the network through some kind of pattern recognition? it doesn't have to be \"biometric data\" in the medical sense, just a sound pattern that triggers a routine.",
